  "text": "Although such a dye uptake impairment implies a direct defect in membrane retrieval, we cannot dismiss the possibility that the reduced exocytosis observed in stoned mutants [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ) causes a coupled reduction in endocytosis. To address this possibility, we examined spaced durations of depolarization stimulation and FM1-43 dye loading. Brief dye loading with high K ϩ for Ͻ1 min (30 sec and 1 min intervals assayed) resulted in a similar defect in stoned dye loading (data not shown; compare with Fig. 2 B) . Dye loading with 5 min of stimulation provided a slight increase in bouton fluorescence intensity in both control and mutant NMJ terminals, but the stoned-specific defect in endocytosis remained unaltered (data not shown). Furthermore, 10 min of high-K ϩ application and dye labeling resulted in no further increase in synaptic dye incorporation of either control or stoned mutant animals, suggesting that the cycling SV pool is maximally saturated after Ͻ5 min of high-K ϩ stimulation. Similarly, to determine whether the striking defects in endocytosis in the embryonic lethal mutants were caused by delayed endocytosis, we applied dye for 5 min in calcium-free saline after 5 min of high-K ϩ stimulation with dye. Longer periods of dye application did not improve the FM1-43 bouton labeling in either wild-type controls or stoned mutants (data not shown). These studies suggest that the recycling SV pool is saturated at these loading times and that stoned mutants have a specific and severe reduction in SV endocytosis. These findings show that the defect in dye uptake is independent of the stimulation duration and probably results from a smaller recycling pool of SVs in stoned mutants.",
